# Pattern: oauth2-proxy in front of an nginx static site

Serving a static site (e.g. an Astro/Hugo build in nginx) behind oauth2-proxy
and Traefik has two sharp edges that produce broken redirects and ugly error
pages. Both are fixed with small config changes.

## nginx leaks the internal port/scheme on redirects

When nginx issues a directory/trailing-slash redirect (request `/docs` →
`Location: /docs/`), by default it builds an **absolute** URL from the request
it sees internally — `http://<pod>:8080/docs/`. Behind oauth2-proxy/Traefik
that leaks the internal port and `http`, and the browser follows it to a dead
address.

Fix: make nginx emit **relative** redirects and never append a port:

```nginx
server {
    listen 8080;
    # Emit relative Location headers; never glue scheme/host/port on.
    absolute_redirect off;
    port_in_redirect  off;

    root /usr/share/nginx/html;
    # ...
}
```

With `absolute_redirect off;` the redirect becomes `Location: /docs/` and the
browser resolves it against the public `https://...` origin correctly.

## Auto-redirect to the IdP (skip the oauth2-proxy button)

By default oauth2-proxy shows its own "Sign in with ..." button page. For a
single central IdP that interstitial is pointless — send users straight to the
login flow:

```
--skip-provider-button=true
```

## Branding the error/sign-in page (optional)

The default oauth2-proxy 403 / sign-in page is unstyled and will show up on
**stale callbacks and expired sessions** (e.g. a user returns to a bookmarked
protected URL after their cookie expired). To replace it with something
branded:

```
--custom-templates-dir=/etc/oauth2-proxy/templates
```

Mount your `sign_in.html` / `error.html` there (a ConfigMap volume). Keep it
minimal — it is only seen on the edges (expiry, denied access).

## Putting it together

This pattern composes with `patterns/app-forwardauth/` (the cluster-wide
oauth2-proxy front door): protect the nginx app's ingress with the ForwardAuth
middlewares, add the `--skip-provider-button` (and any `--custom-templates-dir`)
flags to the shared oauth2-proxy deployment, and set `absolute_redirect off;` /
`port_in_redirect off;` in the app's own nginx config.

For a site that wants a public, link-preview-friendly front page while keeping
content protected, see `patterns/public-landing-protected/`.
